mo (@mmjahanara): Awesome. Thank you, please.

381
00:57:20.730 --> 00:57:21.790
Ansgar Dietrichs: See the screen.

382
00:57:22.530 --> 00:57:27.519
mo (@mmjahanara): Yes. So this is an AIP co-authored by Pierre and I.

383
00:57:27.860 --> 00:57:36.610
mo (@mmjahanara): It's called lineness staking. The motivation is, Ethereum doesn't offer any privacy at base layer, so we want to solve that. That's a key motivation.

384
00:57:37.340 --> 00:57:45.789
mo (@mmjahanara): There are application layer privacy tools, but none of them offer meaningful, plausible deniability, meaning that when you interact with them, it's obvious you're seeking privacy.

385
00:57:45.930 --> 00:57:51.550
mo (@mmjahanara): They're not post-quantum, they're small privacy pools, and of an extractive, opinionated, and so on and so forth.

386
00:57:53.240 --> 00:57:54.590
mo (@mmjahanara): Next slide, please.

387
00:57:54.950 --> 00:58:01.450
mo (@mmjahanara): So, yeah, and also validators are backed one of Ethereum, but there is no privacy protection for them.

388
00:58:01.630 --> 00:58:04.609
mo (@mmjahanara): Meaning that when they move, funds from

389
00:58:04.760 --> 00:58:13.099
mo (@mmjahanara): execution layer to the consensus layer, and, like, deposit into Beacon Chain. They revealed that, okay, I'm going to run this validator identity.

390
00:58:13.230 --> 00:58:19.350
mo (@mmjahanara): And you can link it with my iChain, Unchain identity, and maybe potentially extract more information about me.

391
00:58:19.610 --> 00:58:28.210
mo (@mmjahanara): And it's important to note that there is, like, network-level anonymity, and it's a mature, well-studied topic, like, you use MixedNet and,

392
00:58:28.340 --> 00:58:35.479
mo (@mmjahanara): and your routing, and so on and so forth, but for the problem of linking your unchained identity to

393
00:58:36.170 --> 00:58:43.690
mo (@mmjahanara): the consensus… You know, not… there isn't much discussions?

394
00:58:45.790 --> 00:58:59.040
mo (@mmjahanara): And the side effect, or potentially the cherry on the top, is that users who want privacy but don't want to run validators may benefit from this, you know, introduction of privacy for validators.

395
00:59:00.650 --> 00:59:01.979
mo (@mmjahanara): Next slide, please.

396
00:59:03.690 --> 00:59:11.179
mo (@mmjahanara): And in a nutshell, that's, like, the big thing, is we want to introduce a base layer privacy pool, and

397
00:59:11.490 --> 00:59:17.510
mo (@mmjahanara): Route the staking flows through it, so that this privacy pool is big from day one.

398
00:59:17.780 --> 00:59:27.580
mo (@mmjahanara): And could offer a plausible deniability, because, like, it may… using it looks like you're using test-taking flow, you're going to operate a mode, and so on.

399
00:59:29.990 --> 00:59:42.269
mo (@mmjahanara): So, just a simple diagram. Today, when you deposit into the Beacon deposit contract, you reveal that, okay, this is my it, this is my validator key, and this is where I'm going to withdraw to. So…

400
00:59:42.430 --> 00:59:43.650
mo (@mmjahanara): These are all linked.

401
00:59:43.880 --> 00:59:49.229
mo (@mmjahanara): The idea is you deposit in a new version of the Beacon deposit contract.

402
00:59:49.400 --> 00:59:55.379
mo (@mmjahanara): That, doesn't take all this information from you directly, but take them as a hiding commitment, as the hash.

403
00:59:55.600 --> 01:00:12.839
mo (@mmjahanara): And then you can reveal the content later and claim it. And you could use frame transactions, relayers, and so on and so forth to do it without doing it directly from your main account, or the same account that made the deposit.

404
01:00:14.750 --> 01:00:16.939
mo (@mmjahanara): So we call this a two-phase deposit.

405
01:00:19.280 --> 01:00:24.000
mo (@mmjahanara): And so far, what we described in this slide doesn't need any changes in the consensus slave.

406
01:00:25.810 --> 01:00:27.799
mo (@mmjahanara): Next, yes, thank you.

407
01:00:28.120 --> 01:00:36.050
mo (@mmjahanara): so what… what this achieves is, it breaks the link between the validator identity and the…

408
01:00:37.250 --> 01:00:47.840
mo (@mmjahanara): Depositing site, and the withdrawal site, but it doesn't break the link between the validator, you know, public key, validator identity and consensus layer, and withdrawal credential.

409
01:00:48.060 --> 01:00:50.589
mo (@mmjahanara): So, the address that gets the funds?

410
01:00:52.780 --> 01:00:58.049
mo (@mmjahanara): Ultimately, the withdrawal credential doesn't… doesn't have, like, a broken link.

411
01:00:58.170 --> 01:01:05.239
mo (@mmjahanara): So we call this, like, one-sided plausible deniability, and I explained a bit more why that's the case.

412
01:01:13.090 --> 01:01:18.520
mo (@mmjahanara): I see a question, but I respond after I finish, there is a few more slides.

413
01:01:18.630 --> 01:01:24.819
mo (@mmjahanara): The next part of the idea is that applying the same thinking to the withdrawals.

414
01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:37.169
mo (@mmjahanara): basically, we introduce a new… we could introduce a new, withdrawal credential type, say, Type 3 or Type 4. I see there is a Type 3 already in some active EIPs, so that doesn't matter.

415
01:01:37.490 --> 01:01:41.039
mo (@mmjahanara): Don't confuse them. So there's a new,

416
01:01:41.870 --> 01:01:56.099
mo (@mmjahanara): withdrawal credential type. That's basically a commitment to a recipient address rather than an address. So, if you choose that type of withdrawal credential, instead of receiving the funds when you withdraw or when a withdrawal happens for you.

417
01:01:56.250 --> 01:02:04.810
mo (@mmjahanara): Directly, you receive a commitment in a contract, that you can then go and claim by revealing the, you know.

418
01:02:05.210 --> 01:02:10.850
mo (@mmjahanara): The… the… the address inside the… Commitment you made.

419
01:02:11.590 --> 01:02:21.850
mo (@mmjahanara): So, if you go to the next slide, Pierre, I can deliver the punchline. So the punchline is, you could make, you know, pending deposit.

420
01:02:21.960 --> 01:02:35.409
mo (@mmjahanara): In a private beacon deposit contract, and without going through all the validator queue, withdrawal queue, deposit queue, stuff like that, you could directly nullify this and take it to the withdrawal pool.

421
01:02:36.700 --> 01:02:43.430
mo (@mmjahanara): But the funds that come out of the withdrawal pool look like… or are mixed with the funds that, you know.

422
01:02:43.820 --> 01:02:49.580
mo (@mmjahanara): been withdrawn, from the second, consensus?

423
01:02:49.780 --> 01:02:56.760
mo (@mmjahanara): Layer staking. So they offer you a lot of privacy, because there's a ton of activity.

424
01:02:59.530 --> 01:03:04.920
mo (@mmjahanara): And, we already have a POC using LeanVM for the circuits.

425
01:03:05.130 --> 01:03:12.439
mo (@mmjahanara): So if you're… I'm sure all of you are familiar, but LeanVM is basically an effort to create a post-quantum,

426
01:03:12.660 --> 01:03:31.070
mo (@mmjahanara): VM that could be across… could be used across Ethereum, like, including verifying signatures in consensus and so on and so forth, but broadly for other things as well. So we implemented these things in LeanVM, and although LeanVM is experimental and not very optimized and so on and so forth, it runs very fast, and

427
01:03:31.610 --> 01:03:45.450
mo (@mmjahanara): works great. And, there are plans, to, implement this in REST. Had tips to Anton, and, others in the privacy transaction, private transaction engineering team in EF.

428
01:03:46.220 --> 01:03:49.179
mo (@mmjahanara): And that's it. So, I already see one question.

429
01:03:51.730 --> 01:03:55.920
mo (@mmjahanara): So the question is, why do we do this at the Beacon contract level?

430
01:03:56.060 --> 01:04:02.050
mo (@mmjahanara): Rather than… any application thing. So I guess one…

431
01:04:02.420 --> 01:04:15.759
mo (@mmjahanara): One big thing is you get plausible deniability in this design, or at least we claim that you get plausible deniability by forcing a lot of legitimate protocol flows into the same, you know.

432
01:04:16.290 --> 01:04:17.480
mo (@mmjahanara): Fool, right?

433
01:04:17.920 --> 01:04:26.040
mo (@mmjahanara): So, if we want to achieve that with the application level thing, we need to force, you know, stakers to go there.

434
01:04:26.270 --> 01:04:33.240
mo (@mmjahanara): which sounds, not very achievable. Like, I understand we could implement this protocol

435
01:04:33.380 --> 01:04:41.300
mo (@mmjahanara): primitive as a contract or as an application, and then make it a protocol rule that everybody should pass through that, the withdrawals and deposits?

436
01:04:41.300 --> 01:04:51.630
Potuz: Oh, no, no, what I mean is, why can't you just use any privacy pool at all? Just use any privacy pool that people are using for anything else, like Tornado Cash, or whatever it is.

437
01:04:51.630 --> 01:04:58.929
mo (@mmjahanara): I see your point, yeah. Then you don't get this plausible deniability. Like, say I use Turn of the cash today.

438
01:04:59.310 --> 01:05:03.570
mo (@mmjahanara): And my address is immediately flagged as somebody who's seeking privacy.

439
01:05:04.240 --> 01:05:11.829
mo (@mmjahanara): But… and the reason is, like, legitimate flows, or quote-unquote legitimate flows, don't do that, usually.

440
01:05:12.330 --> 01:05:24.130
mo (@mmjahanara): But if it's a protocol rule that everybody has to do that, then I could just simply claim I'm participating in a quote-unquote legitimate protocol activity, I'm not actively seeking privacy.

441
01:05:24.510 --> 01:05:26.450
mo (@mmjahanara): So that's the key idea.

442
01:05:26.750 --> 01:05:31.999
mo (@mmjahanara): as I said, like, the EIP in a nutshell is to introduce a privacy pool, or pick a privacy pool.

443
01:05:32.330 --> 01:05:41.339
mo (@mmjahanara): and force the staking flows to go through that. And the staking flows are big, obviously, and that gives you plausible deniability, so on and so forth.

444
01:05:42.510 --> 01:05:48.050
mo (@mmjahanara): I understand it's a sensitive topic, and the reason we are bringing this up here.

445
01:05:48.280 --> 01:05:53.740
mo (@mmjahanara): It's to just gather this kind of feedback, so… Yeah, please let me know.

446
01:06:04.190 --> 01:06:06.259
Ansgar Dietrichs: Potuz, do you have your hand up again?

447
01:06:06.260 --> 01:06:20.809
Potuz: Yeah, so if I understand correctly, an application of this could be, if we phrase the IP in a completely different setup, setting, would be, we want to enshrine a privacy pool that is guaranteed to have a lot of traffic.

448
01:06:20.960 --> 01:06:38.049
Potuz: Therefore, let's have a privacy pool in which every staker is forced to send money there, so that at least we know that this privacy pool is going to have a lot of liquidity. So in that sense, it was just forced to have a privacy pool on L1 that is forced to have a lot of liquidity. If that's the…

449
01:06:38.240 --> 01:06:42.030
Potuz: If that's the EIP, at least you would have some sense to me.

450
01:06:42.710 --> 01:06:45.590
mo (@mmjahanara): That's… that's the intention, yes.

451
01:06:54.590 --> 01:06:55.370
Ansgar Dietrichs: Tony?

452
01:06:58.970 --> 01:07:01.300
Toni Wahrstätter: Yeah, to me, I'm not sure if…

453
01:07:01.690 --> 01:07:06.790
Toni Wahrstätter: Like, the uses of privacies and the people staking, if this is, like,

454
01:07:06.950 --> 01:07:14.009
Toni Wahrstätter: set that harmonizes very well, because, for example, you have, like, 32 ETH requirements for staking.

455
01:07:14.170 --> 01:07:19.309
Toni Wahrstätter: Which is, like, you won't provide privacy to a lot of users there.

456
01:07:20.030 --> 01:07:23.949
Toni Wahrstätter: And also, like, staking has no predictable churn.

457
01:07:24.100 --> 01:07:33.470
Toni Wahrstätter: It's not like your anonymity set, which is rather big, Is actually that helpful?

458
01:07:35.100 --> 01:07:45.460
Toni Wahrstätter: Yeah, I'm not sure about this EAP. To me, it feels like, simply withdrawing and then using a privacy protocol would give you very similar guarantees about privacy.

459
01:07:45.720 --> 01:07:48.150
Toni Wahrstätter: And we won't need to enshrine anything.

460
01:07:50.430 --> 01:07:52.660
mo (@mmjahanara): I can quickly respond to the…

461
01:07:54.720 --> 01:08:08.549
mo (@mmjahanara): To the point Tony has. So, I agree that the churn is not predictable, or, like, fluctuates a lot, but the churn is indeed a lot higher than the churn you get on the typical price equals, at least 10x on the worst days.

462
01:08:09.490 --> 01:08:12.000
mo (@mmjahanara): And often, like, 100x more.

463
01:08:13.900 --> 01:08:28.880
mo (@mmjahanara): And again, the reason it's different from, like, using a privacy application layer is, like, this notion of the power of defaults, or, like, what's the legitimate action. Like, that if you ignore the plausible deniability part.

464
01:08:28.990 --> 01:08:47.340
mo (@mmjahanara): This doesn't make any sense. You are all right. But the idea is to achieve something like the wormhole EIP that, like, can't be achieved without compromising on bit security, but we want to achieve that with, like, without compromising on bit security.

465
01:08:47.380 --> 01:08:49.900
mo (@mmjahanara): So, instead of picking, like,

466
01:08:50.470 --> 01:08:54.909
mo (@mmjahanara): Transferring funds to a random address, which looks like a legitimate action.

467
01:08:55.040 --> 01:09:00.539
mo (@mmjahanara): We picked, like, another legitimate protocol primitive, which could be, like, a bad idea.

468
01:09:01.050 --> 01:09:02.169
mo (@mmjahanara): That's the intention.

469
01:09:05.260 --> 01:09:06.859
Ansgar Dietrichs: Peter?

470
01:09:08.100 --> 01:09:15.630
Peter Miller: Yes, you said that a core part of the IP was having two…

471
01:09:16.410 --> 01:09:20.010
Peter Miller: Compel people who are staking to go through the privacy pool.

472
01:09:20.290 --> 01:09:26.199
Peter Miller: I don't understand how you can do that, because without… because currently there are a bunch of existing mechanisms.

473
01:09:26.350 --> 01:09:30.749
Peter Miller: And we can't disable those existing mechanisms, because we'll break everything, we'll break…

474
01:09:31.310 --> 01:09:34.500
Peter Miller: All of the existing, like, staking pools.

475
01:09:34.859 --> 01:09:42.630
Peter Miller: And if we keep the mechanism, there's nothing to stop users from just using the old ways of doing it, and no one putting anything into this pool.

476
01:09:43.350 --> 01:09:45.839
Peter Miller: So how do we compel people to use the pool?

477
01:09:46.120 --> 01:09:50.859
Peter Miller: without… Also, breaking all current staking infrastructure.

478
01:09:52.609 --> 01:10:03.909
mo (@mmjahanara): Very good point. Indeed, like, you need to, at some point at least, disable the old flow to make sure that this goal is achieved.

479
01:10:04.160 --> 01:10:04.720
Barnabas: You cannot.

480
01:10:09.990 --> 01:10:11.530
mo (@mmjahanara): Like, never, never?

481
01:10:13.470 --> 01:10:18.120
Barnabas: Annually, never, never, yeah. I mean, it's like disabling an opcode.

482
01:10:19.470 --> 01:10:25.580
Barnabas: like, we've been trying to get rid of Seth Destruct for, what, 6 years now? And…

483
01:10:25.810 --> 01:10:28.760
Barnabas: There's still, like, one random guy that's using it, and…

484
01:10:28.930 --> 01:10:36.609
Barnabas: That's why it still hasn't been removed. So, like, removing… The functionality is… is not… It's not easy.

485
01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:39.650
mo (@mmjahanara): I see.

486
01:10:40.410 --> 01:10:50.480
Potuz: I think this is very easy. We can just force every validator to be 0.04, and then the contract is disabled for 004 validators.

487
01:10:50.750 --> 01:11:01.199
Potuz: So, it should be easy to make this kind of changes in particular. It should not affect existing validators, but it would affect every newcoming validator.

488
01:11:01.280 --> 01:11:15.470
Potuz: But, again, this is… this should be analyzed in the form of, we want to enshrine a pool and then force every validator to deposit in that pool, which seems kind of crazy at this stage on L1.

489
01:11:19.100 --> 01:11:23.730
Ansgar Dietrichs: Right. Yeah, I mean, it seems to me like, there's…

490
01:11:24.090 --> 01:11:29.110
